dient descent step to perform. We can make a second-order Taylor series approximation to the function $f( oldsymbol{x})$ aroungd the current point $ oldsymbol{x}^{(0)}$: $f( oldsymbol{x}) \approx f\left( oldsymbol{x}^{(0)}ight)+\left( oldsymbol{x}- oldsymbol{x}^{(0)}ight)^{	op}  oldsymbol{g}+ rac{1}{2}\left( oldsymbol{x}- oldsymbol{x}^{(0)}ight)^{	op}  oldsymbol{H}\left( oldsymbol{x}- oldsymbol{x}^{(0)}ight)$ with learning rate $\epsilon$ $f\left( oldsymbol{x}^{(0)}-\epsilon  oldsymbol{g}ight) \approx f\left( oldsymbol{x}^{(0)}ight)-\epsilon  oldsymbol{g}^{	op}  oldsymbol{g}+ rac{1}{2} \epsilon^{2}  oldsymbol{g}^{	op}  oldsymbol{H}  oldsymbol{g}$ There are three terms here: the original value of the function, the expected improvement due to the slope of the function, and the correction we must apply to account for the curvature of the function. When $ oldsymbol{g}^{	op}  oldsymbol{H}  oldsymbol{g}$ is positive, the optimal stepsoze yields $\epsilon^{*}= rac{ oldsymbol{g}^{	op}  oldsymbol{g}}{ oldsymbol{g}^{	op}  oldsymbol{H}  oldsymbol{g}}$ worst case, optimal step is given by $ rac{1}{\lambda_{\max }}$,determined by the eigenvalues of the Hessian In multiple dimensions, the condition number of the Hessian at this point measures how much the second derivatives differ from each other. When the Hessian has a poor condition number, gradient descent performs poorly. Poor condition number also makes choosing a good step size difficult. Newton’s method, using information from the Hessian matrix to guide the search is based on using a second-order Taylor series expansion to approximate $f( oldsymbol{x}) $ near some point $ oldsymbol{x}^{(0)}$ : $f( oldsymbol{x}) \approx f\left( oldsymbol{x}^{(0)}ight)+\left( oldsymbol{x}- oldsymbol{x}^{(0)}ight)^{	op} 
