^{(i)}( oldsymbol{x})+\sum_{j} \alpha_{j} h^{(j)}( oldsymbol{x})$ and $\mathbb{S}=\lbrace oldsymbol{x} |  orall i, g^{(i)}( oldsymbol{x})=0 	ext { and }  orall j, h^{(j)}( oldsymbol{x}) \leq 0brace$ with equality constraints $g^{(j)}$ and inequality constraints $h^{(j)}$ then $\min _{ oldsymbol{x}} \max _{ oldsymbol{\lambda}} \max _{ oldsymbol{\alpha},  oldsymbol{\alpha} \geq 0} L( oldsymbol{x},  oldsymbol{\lambda},  oldsymbol{\alpha})$ has the same optimal objective function value and set of optimal points $ oldsymbol{x}$ as $\min _{ oldsymbol{x} \in \mathbb{S}} f( oldsymbol{x})$ This follows because any time the constraints are satisfied, $\max _{\lambda} \max _{ oldsymbol{\alpha},  oldsymbol{\alpha} \geq 0} L( oldsymbol{x},  oldsymbol{\lambda},  oldsymbol{\alpha})=f( oldsymbol{x})$ while any time a constraint is violated, $\max _{ oldsymbol{\lambda}} \max _{ oldsymbol{\alpha},  oldsymbol{\alpha} \geq 0} L( oldsymbol{x},  oldsymbol{\lambda},  oldsymbol{\alpha})=\infty$ These properties guarantee that no infeasible point can be optimal, and that the optimum within the feasible points is unchanged. KKT conditions The gradient of the generalized Lagrangian is zero. All constraints on both $ oldsymbol{x}$ and the KKT multipliers are satisfied. The inequality constraints exhibit “complementary slackness”: $ oldsymbol{\alpha} \odot  oldsymbol{h}( oldsymbol{x})=\mathbf{0}$. 4.5 Example: Linear Least Squares $f( oldsymbol{x})= rac{1}{2}| oldsymbol{A}  oldsymbol{x}- oldsymbol{b}|_{2}^{2}$ Gradient descent Newton’s method suppose subject to the constraint $ oldsymbol{x}^{	op}  oldsymbol{x} \leq 1$ we introduce the Lagrangian $L( oldsymbol{x}, \lambda)=f( oldsymbol{x})+\lambda\left( oldsymbol{x}^{	op}  oldsymbol{x}-1ight)$ $\min _{ oldsymbol{x}} \max _{\lambda, \lambda \geq 0} L( oldsymbol{x}, \lambda)$ We can find this value by performing gradient ascent on $\lambda$. To do so, observe $ rac{\partial}{\partial \lambda} L( oldsymbol{x}, \lambda)= oldsymbol{x}^{	op}  oldsym